{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4996, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4996", "issue_numbers": [4889], "base_commit": "81ff4cff4409eb07ffed0dc847a889b2aae5a199", "patch": "diff --git a/RELEASE.md b/RELEASE.md\nindex 83490da5c9..32c49254e8 100644\n--- a/RELEASE.md\n+++ b/RELEASE.md\n@@ -1,68 +1,63 @@\n # Upcoming Release 1.0.0\n ## Major features and improvements\n-## Bug fixes and other changes\n-## Breaking changes to the API\n-## Upcoming deprecations for Kedro 1.0.0\n-## Documentation changes\n-## Community contributions\n-\n-# Release 1.0.0rc3\n-\n-## Major features and improvements\n-Changed `DataCatalog.__getitem__` to raise `DatasetNotFoundError` for missing datasets, aligning with expected dictionary behavior.\n-\n-## Bug fixes and other changes\n-## Breaking changes to the API\n-## Upcoming deprecations for Kedro 1.0.0\n-## Documentation changes\n-## Community contributions\n \n-# Release 1.0.0rc2\n+### Data Catalog\n+* The previously experimental `KedroDataCatalog` has been renamed to `DataCatalog` and is now the default catalog implementation.\n+* It retains the dict-like interface, supports lazy dataset initialisation, and delivers improved performance.\n+* While this change is seamless for users following standard Kedro workflows, it introduces a richer API for programmatic use:\n+  * New pipeline-aware commands, available via both the CLI and interactive environments.\n+  * Simplified handling of dataset factories.\n+  * Centralised pattern resolution via the `CatalogConfigResolver` property.\n+  * Ability to serialise the catalog to configuration and reconstruct it from it.\n \n-## Major features and improvements\n-* Added `--only-missing-outputs` CLI flag to `kedro run`. This flag skips nodes when all their persistent outputs exist.\n-* Removed the `AbstractRunner.run_only_missing()` method, an older and underused API for partial runs. Please use `--only-missing-outputs` CLI instead.\n-\n-## Bug fixes and other changes\n-* Improved namespace validation efficiency to prevent significant slowdowns when creating large pipelines\n-\n-## Breaking changes to the API\n-## Upcoming deprecations for Kedro 1.0.0\n-## Documentation changes\n-## Community contributions\n+Read more in the [Kedro documentation](https://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/catalog-data/advanced_data_catalog_usage/).\n \n-# Release 1.0.0rc1\n \n-## Major features and improvements\n+### Namespaces\n+* Added support for running multiple namespaces within a single session with `--namespaces` CLI option and `namespaces` argument in `KedroSession.run()` method.\n+* Improved namespace validation efficiency to prevent significant slowdowns when creating large pipelines.\n * Added stricter validation to dataset names in the `Node` class, ensuring `.` characters are reserved to be used as part of a namespace.\n * Added a `prefix_datasets_with_namespace` argument to the `Pipeline` class which allows users to turn on or off the prefixing of the namespace to the node inputs, outputs, and parameters.\n+* Changed pipeline filtering for namespace to return exact namespace matches instead of partial matches.\n+\n+\n+### Other features and improvements\n * Changed the default node name to be formed of the function name used in the node suffixed by a secure hash (SHA-256) based on the function, inputs, and outputs, ensuring uniqueness and improved readability.\n * Added an option to select which multiprocessing start method is going to be used on `ParallelRunner` via the `KEDRO_MP_CONTEXT` environment variable.\n-\n-## Bug fixes and other changes\n-* Changed pipeline filtering for namespace to return exact namespace matches instead of partial matches.\n-* Added support for running multiple namespaces within a single session.\n+* Added `--only-missing-outputs` CLI flag to `kedro run`. This flag skips nodes when all their persistent outputs exist.\n * Updated `kedro registry describe` to return the node name property instead of creating its own name for the node.\n+* Removed `pre-commit-hooks` dependency for new project creation.\n \n-## Documentation changes\n-* Updated the `DataCatalog` documentation with improved structure and detailed description of new features.\n-\n-## Community contributions\n \n ## Breaking changes to the API\n+### CLI\n+* `kedro catalog create` command has been removed.\n+* `kedro catalog list`, `kedro catalog rank`, and `kedro catalog resolve` commands have been replaced with `kedro catalog describe-datasets`, `kedro catalog list-patterns` and `kedro catalog resolve-patterns` commands, respectively.\n+* The `kedro run` option `--namespace` has been removed and replaced with `--namespaces`.\n+* The `kedro micropkg` CLI command has been removed as part of the micro-packaging feature deprecation.\n+\n+### API\n * Private methods `_is_project` and `_find_kedro_project` are changed to `is_kedro_project` and `find_kedro_project`.\n * Renamed instances of `extra_params` and `_extra_params` to `runtime_params`.\n * Removed the `modular_pipeline` module and moved functionality to the `pipeline` module instead.\n * Renamed `ModularPipelineError` to `PipelineError`.\n * `Pipeline.grouped_nodes_by_namespace()` was replaced with `group_nodes_by(group_by)`, which supports multiple strategies and returns a list of `GroupedNodes`, improving type safety and consistency for deployment plugin integrations.\n-* The micro-packaging feature and the corresponding `micropkg` CLI command have been removed.\n * Renamed `session_id` parameter to `run_id` in all runner methods and hooks to improve API clarity and prepare for future multi-run session support.\n * Removed the following `DataCatalog` methods: `_get_dataset()`, `add_all()`, `add_feed_dict()`, `list()`, and `shallow_copy()`.\n-* Removed the CLI command `kedro catalog create`.\n-* Changed the output of `runner.run()` \u2014 it now always returns all pipeline outputs, regardless of catalog configuration.\n+* Changed the output of `runner.run()` and `session.run()` \u2014 it now always returns all pipeline outputs, regardless of catalog configuration.\n+* Removed the `AbstractRunner.run_only_missing()` method, an older and underused API for partial runs. Please use `--only-missing-outputs` CLI instead.\n+\n+## Documentation changes\n+* Revamped the look and feel of the Kedro documentation, including a new theme and improved navigation with `mkdocs` as the documentation engine.\n+* Updated the `DataCatalog` documentation with improved structure and detailed description of new features. Read the [DataCatalog documentation here](https://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/catalog-data/introduction/).\n+\n+## Community contributions\n+Many thanks to the following Kedroids for contributing PRs to this release:\n+* [Yury Fedotov](https://github.com/yury-fedotov)\n+* [Kitsios Konstantinos](https://github.com/kitsiosk)\n \n ## Migration guide from Kedro 0.19.* to 1.*\n-[See the migration guide for 1.0.0 in the Kedro documentation](https://docs.kedro.org/en/unreleased/about/migration/).\n+[See the migration guide for 1.0.0 in the Kedro documentation](https://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/about/migration/).\n \n # Release 0.19.14\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Release notes for Kedro 1.0\n## Description\nRelease notes for RC are not full: https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/releases/tag/1.0.0rc1\n\nWe should extend them with all relevant changes for Kedro 1.0\n\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/beca441b741a698efeee7546009f84cfd4d455e0", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/d12b0119a6f7dc4ed9724a2e74b20b4d4cdf3c9e", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/275b3d5c87511c8c73ec4fa606ae4fc84bea422f", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/8ad7f77b5bc2229539201df391dc68e605d5e866", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/03be7315528e5bddafb30e1a912315d9e1f653c0", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/b41d7b8ada50c84120fc338ad741008aa4c5b60a", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/9779a9ec7c7456cd3275339ff7a4aba1c7605c3a", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/23f78adcb64155fffbe057ab66e35d6b75d87495", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/9131252a19ead8142f5f0b7d00b225b2f4a287c5", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/fe6dff673a96f2a56bf01ab233c1bdb3d508cfe2", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a3337ffeb2c9b2ea7e0cbffa67e2a76d95a42eeb", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a7825779b2a826e1d6ef345355698e5765ec2e46", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/26a530dfd83855f3b1d5c79c244947689bedc4e8"], "created_at": "2025-07-21T14:31:19Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4957, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4957", "issue_numbers": [4903], "base_commit": "68b1f925307e05606437ebbcf6849c4f38742d44", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/_static/deindex-old-docs.js b/docs/_static/deindex-old-docs.js\nindex 1de7687ce2..30f6a652dd 100644\n--- a/docs/_static/deindex-old-docs.js\n+++ b/docs/_static/deindex-old-docs.js\n@@ -18,8 +18,9 @@ function _handleReadTheDocsData(data) {\n \n     // Ensure the version is updated after each release of kedro-datasets\n     if (\n-        (projectSlug === \"kedro-datasets\" && versionSlug !== \"kedro-datasets-6.0.0\") ||\n-        (projectSlug !== \"kedro-datasets\" && versionSlug !== \"stable\")\n+        (projectSlug === \"kedro\" && versionSlug !== \"1.0.0\") ||\n+        (projectSlug === \"kedro-viz\" && versionSlug !== \"v12.0.0\") ||\n+        (projectSlug === \"kedro-datasets\" && versionSlug !== \"kedro-datasets-8.0.0\")\n     ) {\n         console.log(\"Non-indexable version detected, injecting meta tag\");\n         const meta = document.createElement(\"meta\");\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Update deindexing script to handle removal of stable slug in docs\n## Description\n\nFollowing the changes outlined in [issue #2823](https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/issues/2823), the Kedro and Kedro-Viz documentation no longer use the `stable` slug. This affects our script [`kedro/docs/_static/deindex-old-docs.js`](https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/1.0.0rc1/docs/javascript/deindex-old-docs.js), which runs before each documentation run and adds `noindex, nofollow` to all doc versions except the stable one.\n\n```\n    if (\n        (projectSlug === \"kedro-datasets\" && versionSlug !== \"kedro-datasets-6.0.0\") ||\n        (projectSlug !== \"kedro-datasets\" && versionSlug !== \"stable\")\n    ) \n```\n\n### Short-term solution\n\nUpdate the script to hardcode the current latest stable versions of Kedro and Kedro-Viz.\n\n### Long-term solution\n\nConduct a spike to explore an automated approach for identifying the latest stable version.\n\n", "hints_text": "Agreed with short term & long term \ud83d\udc4d\ud83c\udffc \nI investigated the current state of the `stable` docs and checked its status in Google Search Console.\n\nAs I understand it, we no longer serve a **physical `stable` version** of the docs. Instead, requests to:\n\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/\n\nare redirected to:\n\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/0.19.14/\n\nPreviously, we had a dedicated `stable/` build (copied from the latest release). We **excluded the `noindex` meta tag** from the `stable` pages, but applied it to all other versioned pages - including the latest release like `0.19.14`. This ensured that:\n\n- Google indexed only the `stable/` version\n- Search results consistently pointed to `/stable/...` URLs\n- We retained stable search rankings even when the underlying content changed\n- When a new version was released, only the changed content of few pages needed re-indexing - not the URLs\n\nThis worked well and kept Kedro\u2019s search presence both current and stable.\n\n---\n\n### Current Issue\n\nNow that `stable/` is just a redirect to a versioned page that contains `<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"noindex\">`, Google is no longer indexing these pages properly. Even if we remove the `noindex` tag from the latest version (e.g. `0.19.14`) as proposed as a short-term solution in current issue, this introduces new problems:\n\n- Google will index `/0.19.14/` instead of `/stable/`, meaning search links become outdated with every new release.\n- Each release causes a full reindexing and re-ranking of URLs (and this is a really long and unpredictable process, can take weeks), reducing SEO stability.\n- This issue is visible in our datasets docs:\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/projects/kedro-datasets/en/kedro-datasets-7.0.0/\nwhere there\u2019s no `stable/` and search results often point to outdated versions.\n\n---\n\n### Proposal\n\nI'd like to propose that we **reintroduce a physical `stable/` build**, as we had previously - a full copy of the latest released version. This would:\n\n- Restore consistent and indexable `/stable/` URLs and search ranking stability\n- Avoid confusion from outdated version links in search results\n\nwdyt @astrojuanlu , @merelcht ?\n\nThanks @DimedS. First of all, your assessment is correct: `/en/stable` is now an HTTP 302 FOUND redirect to the default version (nowadays 0.19.14).\n\nHowever, I'm not sure I fully understand your risk assessment. I just checked a few `/en/stable` pages on Google Search Console and they seem to be indexed properly. For example, `https://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/tutorial/create_a_pipeline.html` was last crawled 2 days ago.\n\n<img width=\"1586\" height=\"1553\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a9260cb9-70ea-491d-8e91-1930ce8a1664\" />\n\nLooks like, in any case, the system continues to work normally for now?\nI noticed the same thing, @astrojuanlu. What concerns me is that when you look at the \"Crawled page\" section for the link you mentioned, there's no `noindex` meta tag shown - even though the tag is currently present on the page. The document last update date is listed as March 25, which I believe is before the `noindex` tag was introduced. \n\nSo to me, it seems that although Googlebot crawled the page again 2\u20133 days ago, the actual content wasn't refreshed - and that\u2019s why it still appears indexed. In reality, everything is currently working as expected, just like it did before.\n\nHowever, my concern is that if we leave things as they are, the indexed documentation will gradually become more outdated - because future changes won\u2019t be picked up due to the `noindex` tag on all versioned pages. \n\nIf we remove the `noindex` tag from last release versions, Google will eventually start indexing those pages again, but under their real versioned URLs like `https://docs.kedro.org/en/0.19.14/starters/starters.html`, which could introduce inconsistency and clutter in search results.\n\nAll of these are valid concerns, and I agree they reflect problems that can potentially happen in the future. However, at the moment we don't have strong, solid evidence that it's already happening. In fact, since June 19th the number of indexed pages has continued to go up:\n\n<img width=\"746\" height=\"454\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/23ed1ee5-dadc-44dc-a5b5-fa80ac58fbb6\" />\n\nIn addition, the physical `/stable` version cannot be reintroduced in `kedro-datasets` (because it's a subfolder in a monorepo), so this is a problem we have to solve on its own anyway.\n\nI'd still update the scripts to hardcode the new versions, see how that plays out on a longer timeframe, and continue monitoring the issue just in case.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Agreed with short term & long term \ud83d\udc4d\ud83c\udffc \nI investigated the current state of the `stable` docs and checked its status in Google Search Console.\n\nAs I understand it, we no longer serve a **physical `stable` version** of the docs. Instead, requests to:\n\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/\n\nare redirected to:\n\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/0.19.14/\n\nPreviously, we had a dedicated `stable/` build (copied from the latest release). We **excluded the `noindex` meta tag** from the `stable` pages, but applied it to all other versioned pages - including the latest release like `0.19.14`. This ensured that:\n\n- Google indexed only the `stable/` version\n- Search results consistently pointed to `/stable/...` URLs\n- We retained stable search rankings even when the underlying content changed\n- When a new version was released, only the changed content of few pages needed re-indexing - not the URLs\n\nThis worked well and kept Kedro\u2019s search presence both current and stable.\n\n---\n\n### Current Issue\n\nNow that `stable/` is just a redirect to a versioned page that contains `<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"noindex\">`, Google is no longer indexing these pages properly. Even if we remove the `noindex` tag from the latest version (e.g. `0.19.14`) as proposed as a short-term solution in current issue, this introduces new problems:\n\n- Google will index `/0.19.14/` instead of `/stable/`, meaning search links become outdated with every new release.\n- Each release causes a full reindexing and re-ranking of URLs (and this is a really long and unpredictable process, can take weeks), reducing SEO stability.\n- This issue is visible in our datasets docs:\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/projects/kedro-datasets/en/kedro-datasets-7.0.0/\nwhere there\u2019s no `stable/` and search results often point to outdated versions.\n\n---\n\n### Proposal\n\nI'd like to propose that we **reintroduce a physical `stable/` build**, as we had previously - a full copy of the latest released version. This would:\n\n- Restore consistent and indexable `/stable/` URLs and search ranking stability\n- Avoid confusion from outdated version links in search results\n\nwdyt @astrojuanlu , @merelcht ?\n\nThanks @DimedS. First of all, your assessment is correct: `/en/stable` is now an HTTP 302 FOUND redirect to the default version (nowadays 0.19.14).\n\nHowever, I'm not sure I fully understand your risk assessment. I just checked a few `/en/stable` pages on Google Search Console and they seem to be indexed properly. For example, `https://docs.kedro.org/en/stable/tutorial/create_a_pipeline.html` was last crawled 2 days ago.\n\n<img width=\"1586\" height=\"1553\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a9260cb9-70ea-491d-8e91-1930ce8a1664\" />\n\nLooks like, in any case, the system continues to work normally for now?\nI noticed the same thing, @astrojuanlu. What concerns me is that when you look at the \"Crawled page\" section for the link you mentioned, there's no `noindex` meta tag shown - even though the tag is currently present on the page. The document last update date is listed as March 25, which I believe is before the `noindex` tag was introduced. \n\nSo to me, it seems that although Googlebot crawled the page again 2\u20133 days ago, the actual content wasn't refreshed - and that\u2019s why it still appears indexed. In reality, everything is currently working as expected, just like it did before.\n\nHowever, my concern is that if we leave things as they are, the indexed documentation will gradually become more outdated - because future changes won\u2019t be picked up due to the `noindex` tag on all versioned pages. \n\nIf we remove the `noindex` tag from last release versions, Google will eventually start indexing those pages again, but under their real versioned URLs like `https://docs.kedro.org/en/0.19.14/starters/starters.html`, which could introduce inconsistency and clutter in search results.\n\nAll of these are valid concerns, and I agree they reflect problems that can potentially happen in the future. However, at the moment we don't have strong, solid evidence that it's already happening. In fact, since June 19th the number of indexed pages has continued to go up:\n\n<img width=\"746\" height=\"454\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/23ed1ee5-dadc-44dc-a5b5-fa80ac58fbb6\" />\n\nIn addition, the physical `/stable` version cannot be reintroduced in `kedro-datasets` (because it's a subfolder in a monorepo), so this is a problem we have to solve on its own anyway.\n\nI'd still update the scripts to hardcode the new versions, see how that plays out on a longer timeframe, and continue monitoring the issue just in case.\n> All of these are valid concerns...\n\nyou right, let's try and observe effects in 1-2 weeks, I made a PR: #4957 \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/d5b667c9948217ec82a82cd9f7e4d7466c1e1acd", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/38103c7dc0c56f2e7ba0d7a8f0ba9ba127119538", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/e48658893f2416e1aa9275721184f0dde207b609"], "created_at": "2025-07-09T09:13:20Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4976, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4976", "issue_numbers": [4909], "base_commit": "fc31573a4a9203c1386b4b869562ecfac2c14b71", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md b/docs/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md\nindex afbfdf2fb7..6d03838590 100644\n--- a/docs/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md\n+++ b/docs/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md\n@@ -288,21 +288,21 @@ You can use multiple placeholders in the same pattern. For example, consider the\n entries share `type`, `file_format` and `save_args`:\n \n ```yaml\n-processing.factory_data:\n+processing-factory_data:\n   type: spark.SparkDataset\n   filepath: data/processing/factory_data.parquet\n   file_format: parquet\n   save_args:\n     mode: overwrite\n \n-processing.process_data:\n+processing-process_data:\n   type: spark.SparkDataset\n   filepath: data/processing/process_data.parquet\n   file_format: parquet\n   save_args:\n     mode: overwrite\n \n-modelling.metrics:\n+modelling-metrics:\n   type: spark.SparkDataset\n   filepath: data/modelling/factory_data.parquet\n   file_format: parquet\n@@ -313,7 +313,7 @@ modelling.metrics:\n This could be generalised to the following pattern:\n \n ```yaml\n-\"{layer}.{dataset_name}\":\n+\"{layer}-{dataset_name}\":\n   type: spark.SparkDataset\n   filepath: data/{layer}/{dataset_name}.parquet\n   file_format: parquet\ndiff --git a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\nindex 9831380880..195fa077f6 100644\n--- a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n+++ b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n@@ -15,6 +15,7 @@\n from typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any\n \n import dynaconf\n+import importlib_resources\n import yaml\n from dynaconf import LazySettings\n from dynaconf.validator import ValidationError, Validator\n@@ -420,7 +421,7 @@ def find_pipelines(raise_errors: bool = False) -> dict[str, Pipeline]:  # noqa:\n \n     # Handle the case that a project doesn't have a pipelines directory.\n     try:\n-        pipelines_package = importlib.resources.files(f\"{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines\")\n+        pipelines_package = importlib_resources.files(f\"{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines\")\n     except ModuleNotFoundError as exc:\n         if str(exc) == f\"No module named '{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines'\":\n             return pipelines_dict\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex 545405d9d7..da0d0faaab 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -21,6 +21,7 @@ dependencies = [\n     \"fsspec>=2021.4\",\n     \"gitpython>=3.0\",\n     \"importlib-metadata>=3.6,<9.0\",  # This can be removed when we drop 3.9 support\n+    \"importlib_resources>=1.3,<7.0\",  # This can be removed when we drop 3.9 support\n     \"kedro-telemetry>=0.5.0\",\n     \"more_itertools>=8.14.0\",\n     \"omegaconf>=2.1.1\",\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Warning about dot in dataset name contradicts dataset factory docs\n## Description\nIn the docs about dataset factories we use the dot notation in examples: https://docs.kedro.org/en/1.0.0rc1/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories/#how-to-generalise-datasets-of-the-same-type-in-different-layers\n\nBut now in the release candidate you see: \n```\nUserWarning: Dataset name '01_raw.shuttles' contains '.' characters, which is not recommended as   warnings.py:110\n                             the dot notation is reserved for automatic namespacing in Kedro. Consider using a different naming convention.\n```\nwhen you use the dot. \n\nI think this is confusing and we should update our docs to give examples that don't produce warnings.\n\n\n", "hints_text": "Thanks, @merelcht. I think these are a bit tricky questions.\n\nIn the given example, the warning won\u2019t be triggered if two namespaced pipelines (or nodes) are associated with the same namespaced datasets. So in my view, the use of a dot (`\".\"`) in the example actually reflects our recommendation on how to properly structure pipelines using namespaces. Technically, we could replace the dot with an underscore (`\"_\"`), but I\u2019m not sure it would add any real benefit.\n\nMy main concern is with the warning itself - it\u2019s not ideal, as it can be triggered even in valid scenarios. For example, the warning may appear when one namespaced pipeline takes the output of another as input, which is a perfectly valid situation. That\u2019s why in [#4797](https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/pull/4797), we changed it from an error to a warning - to simply inform users that dots should be used only in namespaces.\n\nWould be glad to hear any additional opinions, @ankatiyar \n\nI'm surprised because the warning should only be triggered when the dataset names in the pipeline inputs or outputs contain dots, i.e.\n```\nPipeline(\n  ...\ninputs = \"namespace.x\",\n)\n```\nBecause, the namespace should automatically be prefixed by Kedro. But it is expected to define namespaced datasets in the `catalog.yml` like this anyway, with or without dataset factories. \n> I'm surprised because the warning should only be triggered when the dataset names in the pipeline inputs or outputs contain dots, i.e.\n> \n> ```\n> Pipeline(\n>   ...\n> inputs = \"namespace.x\",\n> )\n> ```\n> \n> Because, the namespace should automatically be prefixed by Kedro. But it is expected to define namespaced datasets in the `catalog.yml` like this anyway, with or without dataset factories.\n\nWell yes the issue is that when you use the dataset factory in the catalog, e.g. like this for spaceflights:\n\n```yml\n\"{layer}.{dataset_name}\":\n  type: pandas.CSVDataset\n  filepath: data/{layer}/{dataset_name}.csv\n```\n\nRequires updates in the pipeline files to then mention `01_raw.companies` and `01_raw.reviews`. \n@DimedS I'm not sure I fully understand what you mean with \n\n> In the given example, the warning won\u2019t be triggered if two namespaced pipelines (or nodes) are associated with the same namespaced datasets. So in my view, the use of a dot (\".\") in the example actually reflects our recommendation on how to properly structure pipelines using namespaces. \n\nDo you mean a pipeline where two pipelines have the same namespace? \n\nThe way I see it, this example: https://docs.kedro.org/en/1.0.0rc1/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories/#how-to-generalise-datasets-of-the-same-type-in-different-layers isn't actually about **namespaces** at all, and that's why IMO the error is so confusing. \n\n> Technically, we could replace the dot with an underscore (\"_\"), but I\u2019m not sure it would add any real benefit.\n\nI think that \u261d\ufe0f actually would be a better suggestion because it gets rid of any confusion with namespaces. \nOoh sorry I assumed this was related to using dataset factories for namespaces. For examples of how to use dataset factories for cases other than namespaces, we should use a different separator, like underscore like Dmitry suggested in the docs. The idea for the warning is to show that the dot notation is reserved (not very strictly) for namespaces so I think it's worth updating our docs to follow our own recommendations.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thanks, @merelcht. I think these are a bit tricky questions.\n\nIn the given example, the warning won\u2019t be triggered if two namespaced pipelines (or nodes) are associated with the same namespaced datasets. So in my view, the use of a dot (`\".\"`) in the example actually reflects our recommendation on how to properly structure pipelines using namespaces. Technically, we could replace the dot with an underscore (`\"_\"`), but I\u2019m not sure it would add any real benefit.\n\nMy main concern is with the warning itself - it\u2019s not ideal, as it can be triggered even in valid scenarios. For example, the warning may appear when one namespaced pipeline takes the output of another as input, which is a perfectly valid situation. That\u2019s why in [#4797](https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/pull/4797), we changed it from an error to a warning - to simply inform users that dots should be used only in namespaces.\n\nWould be glad to hear any additional opinions, @ankatiyar \n\nI'm surprised because the warning should only be triggered when the dataset names in the pipeline inputs or outputs contain dots, i.e.\n```\nPipeline(\n  ...\ninputs = \"namespace.x\",\n)\n```\nBecause, the namespace should automatically be prefixed by Kedro. But it is expected to define namespaced datasets in the `catalog.yml` like this anyway, with or without dataset factories. \n> I'm surprised because the warning should only be triggered when the dataset names in the pipeline inputs or outputs contain dots, i.e.\n> \n> ```\n> Pipeline(\n>   ...\n> inputs = \"namespace.x\",\n> )\n> ```\n> \n> Because, the namespace should automatically be prefixed by Kedro. But it is expected to define namespaced datasets in the `catalog.yml` like this anyway, with or without dataset factories.\n\nWell yes the issue is that when you use the dataset factory in the catalog, e.g. like this for spaceflights:\n\n```yml\n\"{layer}.{dataset_name}\":\n  type: pandas.CSVDataset\n  filepath: data/{layer}/{dataset_name}.csv\n```\n\nRequires updates in the pipeline files to then mention `01_raw.companies` and `01_raw.reviews`. \n@DimedS I'm not sure I fully understand what you mean with \n\n> In the given example, the warning won\u2019t be triggered if two namespaced pipelines (or nodes) are associated with the same namespaced datasets. So in my view, the use of a dot (\".\") in the example actually reflects our recommendation on how to properly structure pipelines using namespaces. \n\nDo you mean a pipeline where two pipelines have the same namespace? \n\nThe way I see it, this example: https://docs.kedro.org/en/1.0.0rc1/catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories/#how-to-generalise-datasets-of-the-same-type-in-different-layers isn't actually about **namespaces** at all, and that's why IMO the error is so confusing. \n\n> Technically, we could replace the dot with an underscore (\"_\"), but I\u2019m not sure it would add any real benefit.\n\nI think that \u261d\ufe0f actually would be a better suggestion because it gets rid of any confusion with namespaces. \nOoh sorry I assumed this was related to using dataset factories for namespaces. For examples of how to use dataset factories for cases other than namespaces, we should use a different separator, like underscore like Dmitry suggested in the docs. The idea for the warning is to show that the dot notation is reserved (not very strictly) for namespaces so I think it's worth updating our docs to follow our own recommendations.\nI agree with you, @merelcht and @ankatiyar - let\u2019s not mix that example with namespaces, even if the example itself is correct. I\u2019ve made those fixes in #4976 \n\nRegarding @merelcht\u2019s question:\nI mean that this example is already correct, and no warning should be triggered if there are two pipelines, each with its own namespace.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/36e2f88980b1c2a8a3621f632fb0e1e65462c195", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/9529c936f4986f7bbf016c35d95d53177c203752", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/30dbfa3d14ee4cdb00b3c16c1cf93b970aa18dba", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/b8e56d6ad2ef33ebc0a863ed6de65bea09bbd973"], "created_at": "2025-07-16T11:54:25Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4964, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4964", "issue_numbers": [4916], "base_commit": "48e34d0b9e0f0589a4257fd443f971e7495f7d9f", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/catalog-data/data_catalog.md b/docs/catalog-data/data_catalog.md\nindex 47d34ba177..951037f5fb 100644\n--- a/docs/catalog-data/data_catalog.md\n+++ b/docs/catalog-data/data_catalog.md\n@@ -225,8 +225,10 @@ To illustrate this, consider the following catalog entry for a dataset named `ca\n cars:\n   filepath: s3://my_bucket/cars.csv\n   type: pandas.CSVDataset\n- ```\n+```\n+\n You can overwrite this catalog entry in `conf/local/catalog.yml` to point to a locally stored file instead:\n+\n ```yaml\n cars:\n   filepath: data/01_raw/cars.csv\ndiff --git a/docs/getting-started/faq.md b/docs/getting-started/faq.md\nindex 522a4d7b6f..5d83bb64ea 100644\n--- a/docs/getting-started/faq.md\n+++ b/docs/getting-started/faq.md\n@@ -52,6 +52,15 @@ This is a growing set of technical FAQs. The [product FAQs on the Kedro website]\n * [How do I load credentials through environment variables](../configure/advanced_configuration.md#how-to-load-credentials-through-environment-variables)?\n * [How do I use Kedro with different project structure?](../tutorials/settings.md#use-kedro-without-the-src-folder)\n \n+## Data Catalog\n+* [How do I create dataset entries in catalog.yml?](../catalog-data/data_catalog.md)\n+* [How do I use the same file with different formats using transcoding?](../catalog-data/data_catalog_yaml_examples.md#read-the-same-file-using-different-datasets-with-transcoding)\n+* [How do I use dataset factories?](../catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md)\n+* [How do I override the default dataset creation with a default dataset factory pattern?](../catalog-data/kedro_dataset_factories.md#how-to-override-the-default-dataset-creation-with-dataset-factories)\n+* [How do I load and save incremental or partitioned datasets?](../catalog-data/partitioned_and_incremental_datasets.md)\n+\n+## Advanced topics\n+* [How do I use the `DataCatalog` programmatically in code?](../catalog-data/advanced_data_catalog_usage.md)\n \n ## Nodes and pipelines\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Add catalog as topic to FAQs\n## Description\nWe have a summary page with questions that link to several topics. We can link the new catalog questions ther too.\n\n### Documentation page (if applicable)\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/1.0.0rc1/getting-started/faq/\n\n\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/e5e76afc521785ccedd6f1c4a4893742688f5583", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/dfd7b4166f4a8e7a24f7dfe6a829767cc2d9b029"], "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:34:48Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 5187, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-5187", "issue_numbers": [4939], "base_commit": "d02bc0bd3c79728e3fd57bfe44bf57dde9e0edcf", "patch": "diff --git a/RELEASE.md b/RELEASE.md\nindex ea87a922e4..d23aed98b8 100644\n--- a/RELEASE.md\n+++ b/RELEASE.md\n@@ -5,6 +5,7 @@\n * Dropped support for Python 3.9 (EOL Oct 2025). Minimum supported version is now 3.10.\n \n ## Bug fixes and other changes\n+* Bumped `click` dependency to support versions 8.2.0 and above.\n \n ## Documentation changes\n * Added a note on programmatically creating lambdas when lazily saving a `PartionedDataset`.\ndiff --git a/kedro/framework/cli/cli.py b/kedro/framework/cli/cli.py\nindex 663067b4f2..9d0a6d8900 100644\n--- a/kedro/framework/cli/cli.py\n+++ b/kedro/framework/cli/cli.py\n@@ -211,7 +211,7 @@ def main(\n             raise\n \n     @property\n-    def global_groups(self) -> Sequence[click.MultiCommand]:\n+    def global_groups(self) -> Sequence[click.Group]:\n         \"\"\"Property which loads all global command groups from plugins and\n         combines them with the built-in ones (eventually overriding the\n         built-in ones if they are redefined by plugins).\n@@ -219,7 +219,7 @@ def global_groups(self) -> Sequence[click.MultiCommand]:\n         return [cli, *load_entry_points(\"global\"), global_commands]\n \n     @property\n-    def project_groups(self) -> Sequence[click.MultiCommand]:\n+    def project_groups(self) -> Sequence[click.Group]:\n         \"\"\"Property which loads all project command groups from the\n         project and the plugins, then combines them with the built-in ones.\n         Built-in commands can be overridden by plugins, which can be\ndiff --git a/kedro/framework/cli/utils.py b/kedro/framework/cli/utils.py\nindex 6d6eddc444..c0dd0d4555 100644\n--- a/kedro/framework/cli/utils.py\n+++ b/kedro/framework/cli/utils.py\n@@ -17,6 +17,7 @@\n \n if TYPE_CHECKING:\n     from collections.abc import Callable, Iterable, Sequence\n+\n from importlib import import_module\n from itertools import chain\n from pathlib import Path\n@@ -131,7 +132,7 @@ def validate_conf_source(ctx: click.Context, param: Any, value: str) -> str | No\n class CommandCollection(click.CommandCollection):\n     \"\"\"Modified from the Click one to still run the source groups function.\"\"\"\n \n-    def __init__(self, *groups: tuple[str, Sequence[click.MultiCommand]]):\n+    def __init__(self, *groups: tuple[str, Sequence[click.Group]]):\n         self.groups = [\n             (title, self._merge_same_name_collections(cli_list))\n             for title, cli_list in groups\n@@ -153,9 +154,9 @@ def __init__(self, *groups: tuple[str, Sequence[click.MultiCommand]]):\n \n     @staticmethod\n     def _merge_same_name_collections(\n-        groups: Sequence[click.MultiCommand],\n+        groups: Sequence[click.Group],\n     ) -> list[click.CommandCollection]:\n-        named_groups: defaultdict[str, list[click.MultiCommand]] = defaultdict(list)\n+        named_groups: defaultdict[str, list[click.Group]] = defaultdict(list)\n         helps: defaultdict[str, list] = defaultdict(list)\n         for group in groups:\n             named_groups[group.name].append(group)  # type: ignore[index]\n@@ -351,7 +352,7 @@ def _safe_load_entry_point(\n         return\n \n \n-def load_entry_points(name: str) -> Sequence[click.MultiCommand]:\n+def load_entry_points(name: str) -> Sequence[click.Group]:\n     \"\"\"Load package entry point commands.\n \n     Args:\n@@ -529,12 +530,12 @@ def list_commands(self, ctx: click.Context) -> list[str]:\n \n     def get_command(  # type: ignore[override]\n         self, ctx: click.Context, cmd_name: str\n-    ) -> click.BaseCommand | click.Command | None:\n+    ) -> click.Command | None:\n         if cmd_name in self.lazy_subcommands:\n             return self._lazy_load(cmd_name)\n         return super().get_command(ctx, cmd_name)\n \n-    def _lazy_load(self, cmd_name: str) -> click.BaseCommand:\n+    def _lazy_load(self, cmd_name: str) -> click.Command:\n         # lazily loading a command, first get the module name and attribute name\n         import_path = self.lazy_subcommands[cmd_name]\n         modname, cmd_object_name = import_path.rsplit(\".\", 1)\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex 1bd90d1198..e9ab2bcab6 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -15,7 +15,7 @@ dependencies = [\n     \"attrs>=21.3\",\n     \"build>=0.7.0\",\n     \"cachetools>=4.1\",\n-    \"click>=4.0,<8.2.0\",\n+    \"click>=8.2\",\n     \"cookiecutter>=2.1.1,<3.0\",\n     \"dynaconf>=3.1.2,<4.0\",\n     \"fsspec>=2021.4\",\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/framework/cli/pipeline/test_pipeline.py b/tests/framework/cli/pipeline/test_pipeline.py\nindex de21d6cba8..cb7f778c89 100644\n--- a/tests/framework/cli/pipeline/test_pipeline.py\n+++ b/tests/framework/cli/pipeline/test_pipeline.py\n@@ -506,7 +506,15 @@ def test_pipeline_delete_confirmation(\n             f\"Are you sure you want to delete pipeline '{PIPELINE_NAME}'\"\n             in result.output\n         )\n-        assert \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n+        # Click < 8.2: \"random\" input asks again, gets EOF, uses default (no)\n+        #              -> \"Deletion aborted!\"\n+        # Click >= 8.2: \"random\" input with EOF immediately aborts\n+        #               -> \"Aborted!\"\n+        # Valid \"n\" or \"N\" always shows \"Deletion aborted!\"\n+        if input_ == \"random\":\n+            assert \"Aborted!\" in result.output or \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n+        else:\n+            assert \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n \n         assert source_path.is_dir()\n         assert tests_path.is_dir()\n@@ -546,7 +554,15 @@ def test_pipeline_delete_confirmation_skip(\n             f\"Are you sure you want to delete pipeline '{PIPELINE_NAME}'\"\n             in result.output\n         )\n-        assert \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n+        # Click < 8.2: \"random\" input asks again, gets EOF, uses default (no)\n+        #              -> \"Deletion aborted!\"\n+        # Click >= 8.2: \"random\" input with EOF immediately aborts\n+        #               -> \"Aborted!\"\n+        # Valid \"n\" or \"N\" always shows \"Deletion aborted!\"\n+        if input_ == \"random\":\n+            assert \"Aborted!\" in result.output or \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n+        else:\n+            assert \"Deletion aborted!\" in result.output\n \n         assert tests_path.is_dir()\n         assert params_path.is_file()\ndiff --git a/tests/framework/cli/test_cli.py b/tests/framework/cli/test_cli.py\nindex 8e1ab35402..284943002f 100644\n--- a/tests/framework/cli/test_cli.py\n+++ b/tests/framework/cli/test_cli.py\n@@ -77,7 +77,9 @@ def test_cli(self):\n         \"\"\"Run `kedro` without arguments.\"\"\"\n         result = CliRunner().invoke(cli, [])\n \n-        assert result.exit_code == 0\n+        # Exit code 2: click 8.2+ exits with code 2 when a group is invoked\n+        # without a subcommand\n+        assert result.exit_code == 2\n         assert \"kedro\" in result.output\n \n     def test_print_version(self):\n@@ -200,7 +202,9 @@ def test_help(self):\n         \"\"\"Check that help output includes stub_cli group description.\"\"\"\n         cmd_collection = CommandCollection((\"Commands\", [cli, stub_cli]))\n         result = CliRunner().invoke(cmd_collection, [])\n-        assert result.exit_code == 0\n+        # Exit code 2: click 8.2+ exits with code 2 when a group is invoked\n+        # without a subcommand\n+        assert result.exit_code == 2\n         assert \"Stub CLI group description\" in result.output\n         assert \"Kedro is a CLI\" in result.output\n \n@@ -453,7 +457,9 @@ def test_kedro_cli_no_project(self, mocker, tmp_path):\n \n         result = CliRunner().invoke(kedro_cli, [])\n \n-        assert result.exit_code == 0\n+        # Exit code 2: click 8.2+ exits with code 2 when a group is invoked\n+        # without a subcommand\n+        assert result.exit_code == 2\n         assert \"Global commands from kedro\" in result.output\n         assert \"Project specific commands from kedro\" not in result.output\n \n@@ -487,7 +493,9 @@ def test_kedro_cli_with_project(self, mocker, fake_metadata):\n         ]\n \n         result = CliRunner().invoke(kedro_cli, [])\n-        assert result.exit_code == 0\n+        # Exit code 2: click 8.2+ exits with code 2 when a group is invoked\n+        # without a subcommand\n+        assert result.exit_code == 2\n         assert \"Global commands from kedro\" in result.output\n         assert \"Project specific commands from kedro\" in result.output\n \n@@ -878,9 +886,10 @@ def test_bad_runtime_params(self, fake_project_cli, fake_metadata, bad_arg):\n             fake_project_cli, [\"run\", \"--params\", bad_arg], obj=fake_metadata\n         )\n         assert result.exit_code\n+        # Click 8.2+ sends error messages to stderr, so check result.output\n         assert (\n             \"Item `bad` must contain a key and a value separated by `=`.\"\n-            in result.stdout\n+            in result.output\n         )\n \n     @mark.parametrize(\"bad_arg\", [\"=\", \"=value\", \" =value\"])\n@@ -889,7 +898,8 @@ def test_bad_params_key(self, fake_project_cli, fake_metadata, bad_arg):\n             fake_project_cli, [\"run\", \"--params\", bad_arg], obj=fake_metadata\n         )\n         assert result.exit_code\n-        assert \"Parameter key cannot be an empty string\" in result.stdout\n+        # Click 8.2+ sends error messages to stderr, so check result.output\n+        assert \"Parameter key cannot be an empty string\" in result.output\n \n     @mark.parametrize(\n         \"lv_input, lv_dict\",\ndiff --git a/tests/framework/cli/test_cli_hooks.py b/tests/framework/cli/test_cli_hooks.py\nindex ce21008217..a21e4bd16b 100644\n--- a/tests/framework/cli/test_cli_hooks.py\n+++ b/tests/framework/cli/test_cli_hooks.py\n@@ -86,7 +86,9 @@ def fake_plugin_distribution(mocker):\n class TestKedroCLIHooks:\n     @pytest.mark.parametrize(\n         \"command, exit_code\",\n-        [(\"-V\", 0), (\"info\", 0), (\"pipeline list\", 2), (\"starter\", 0)],\n+        # Exit code 2: click 8.2+ exits with code 2 when a group is invoked\n+        # without a subcommand (applies to 'starter')\n+        [(\"-V\", 0), (\"info\", 0), (\"pipeline list\", 2), (\"starter\", 2)],\n     )\n     def test_kedro_cli_should_invoke_cli_hooks_from_plugin(\n         self,\n@@ -122,5 +124,6 @@ def test_kedro_cli_should_invoke_cli_hooks_from_plugin(\n         # 'pipeline list' isn't actually in the click structure and\n         # return exit code 2 ('invalid usage of some shell built-in command')\n         assert (\n-            f\"After command `{command}` run for project {fake_metadata} (exit: {exit_code})\"\n+            f\"After command `{command}` run for project {fake_metadata} \"\n+            f\"(exit: {exit_code})\"\n         ) in result.output\n", "problem_statement": "Unpin `click<8.2.0`\nAny chance we can unpin `click<8.2.0`?\n\nhttps://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/0da4ec60dba044946c9357b6a0efd018429f95f0/pyproject.toml#L18\n\nThis was done in #4724 to solve some CI failures, but now it conflicts with other packages.\n\n(I was bitten by this while trying to deploy a Kedro project to Airflow)\n", "hints_text": "@merelcht : Click 8.2 has some breaking changes _and_ they dropped support for Python 3.9.\n\nWe want to try and support new versions as well, but for that we first want to understand what changes would we need to do to our code.\nBumping this to a high priority now support for Python 3.9 was dropped for Kedro.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "@merelcht : Click 8.2 has some breaking changes _and_ they dropped support for Python 3.9.\n\nWe want to try and support new versions as well, but for that we first want to understand what changes would we need to do to our code.\nBumping this to a high priority now support for Python 3.9 was dropped for Kedro.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/cf05dd067434f98b9b15aab7eee85390c4f11698", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/fe0cd8edd0a9cc7850add602123288fdfecc51ea", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/e30f13450e84c3ada7c58c26f66fddd1a54c65c3", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a21965e4dcc114ef32d83f782f79a8fe51e30029", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/413c34e8df6eda063f017f0bca85b892ab2277d4", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a49d2a8f3f014a7b5d85749d8316e11dac6f09b5", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/f74d01d109c80272217ac5b2b5f8f4d9b45d82dd", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a1a44f9545c4131834fc27df96e18870075d6216", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/1b1067319e53398d9477c6b9c06d28f3cd57df34", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/c3e94e0bda3d11b876c64e1051ee513e8ca47329", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/b5e96a561d40243657fe810ad88bb8863d49ecd3", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/94263b5439a53bfcec721c430874be80ebb6b816", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a56d27f398c7d49fcfb2215318a76e5253a7d39d", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/98765dbb1a60b64c955c427de2ed0eb427135529"], "created_at": "2025-10-31T13:52:36Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4965, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4965", "issue_numbers": [4951], "base_commit": "5c33b7d43005203ab2213540ceffaff21007e4b2", "patch": "diff --git a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\nindex 195fa077f6..9831380880 100644\n--- a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n+++ b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n@@ -15,7 +15,6 @@\n from typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any\n \n import dynaconf\n-import importlib_resources\n import yaml\n from dynaconf import LazySettings\n from dynaconf.validator import ValidationError, Validator\n@@ -421,7 +420,7 @@ def find_pipelines(raise_errors: bool = False) -> dict[str, Pipeline]:  # noqa:\n \n     # Handle the case that a project doesn't have a pipelines directory.\n     try:\n-        pipelines_package = importlib_resources.files(f\"{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines\")\n+        pipelines_package = importlib.resources.files(f\"{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines\")\n     except ModuleNotFoundError as exc:\n         if str(exc) == f\"No module named '{PACKAGE_NAME}.pipelines'\":\n             return pipelines_dict\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex d8d643db8d..545405d9d7 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -20,8 +20,7 @@ dependencies = [\n     \"dynaconf>=3.1.2,<4.0\",\n     \"fsspec>=2021.4\",\n     \"gitpython>=3.0\",\n-    \"importlib-metadata>=3.6,<9.0\",\n-    \"importlib_resources>=1.3,<7.0\",  # The `files()` API was introduced in `importlib_resources` 1.3 and Python 3.9.\n+    \"importlib-metadata>=3.6,<9.0\",  # This can be removed when we drop 3.9 support\n     \"kedro-telemetry>=0.5.0\",\n     \"more_itertools>=8.14.0\",\n     \"omegaconf>=2.1.1\",\n@@ -30,7 +29,6 @@ dependencies = [\n     \"pre-commit-hooks\",\n     \"PyYAML>=4.2,<7.0\",\n     \"rich>=12.0,<15.0\",\n-    \"rope>=0.21,<2.0\",  # subject to LGPLv3 license\n     \"toml>=0.10.0\",\n     \"typing_extensions>=4.0\",\n ]\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Drop unneeded dependencies\n- `importlib-metadata`: `importlib.metadata` was introduced in Python 3.8, we can probably use the stdlib now\n- `importlib-resources`: `importlib.resources.files` was introduced in Python 3.9\n- `rope`: unused after we dropped micropackaging in #4746\n\nExtras:\n\n- `pre-commit-hooks`: Added in #3436, it was pulled for just 1 function and is a blocker for Pyodide/PyScript support https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/discussions/4278 but it requires vendoring the logic\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "- #4965 for `importlib_resources` & `rope`\n- `importlib-metadata` blocked by #4966 \n- `pre-commit-hooks` TODO\nI need opinions which way would be best to deal with removal of `pre-commit-hooks` from dependencies. For context, we use it for the one function `fix_requirements` which sorts the `requirements.txt` while preserving comments and was added in #3436 It is used while creation of a new project in `post_gen_hooks` in the starters & new blank project template.\n- One way is to copy over the `fix_requirements()` function or something similar into our code base and use it\n- The other is to get rid of this sorting. Remove `sort_requirements` first from `spaceflights-pandas` and `spaceflights-pyspark` (https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro-starters/pull/289) and then from Kedro code base. \nSorting the requirements files in alphabetic order is nice but doesn't merit adding another dependency I think, especially one that is used for development so often and might clash with user environments.\n\nThe full logic is 150 lines of code and it's MIT licensed https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks/blob/v5.0.0/pre_commit_hooks/requirements_txt_fixer.py either we vendor it ourselves, or we proceed with removing this functionality.\nI'm leaning towards removing the sorting of requirements, confirmed with @SajidAlamQB in https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro-starters/pull/289 that it's safe to do. @astrojuanlu \nI'd be in favor of removing the sorting of requirements as well. After we moved the main source of requirements to pyproject.toml that whole function became kind of a vestigial thing. If it's not gonna make any linter scream or anything of the sort, it's more advantageous to remove a dependency instead of adding something else that we'd have to maintain.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/db5df1d0316ff6761ce9aa10d86d45cf57a30e53", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/66a42b8f17273d86339288b6bd379456f55db504", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/9cead6b5cf960bba38c14d1cb4f55826e1917489", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/cc804c30388560c19e2aba6448a90e284e80873f", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/041da0736030e984a01411e9124134a1073e56e3"], "created_at": "2025-07-11T10:03:18Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 4971, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-4971", "issue_numbers": [4951], "base_commit": "f6a0c93a28ab71f7612461e5296c4395820ade23", "patch": "diff --git a/kedro/templates/project/hooks/utils.py b/kedro/templates/project/hooks/utils.py\nindex 570e262c86..4212466979 100644\n--- a/kedro/templates/project/hooks/utils.py\n+++ b/kedro/templates/project/hooks/utils.py\n@@ -2,8 +2,6 @@\n import shutil\n import toml\n \n-from pre_commit_hooks.requirements_txt_fixer import fix_requirements\n-\n current_dir = Path.cwd()\n \n # Requirements for linting tools\n@@ -216,13 +214,3 @@ def setup_template_tools(\n         # Remove requirements used by example pipelines\n         _remove_from_file(requirements_file_path, example_pipeline_requirements)\n         _remove_extras_from_kedro_datasets(requirements_file_path)\n-\n-\n-def sort_requirements(requirements_file_path: Path) -> None:\n-    \"\"\"Sort entries in `requirements.txt`, writing back changes, if any.\n-\n-    Args:\n-        requirements_file_path (Path): The path to the `requirements.txt` file.\n-    \"\"\"\n-    with open(requirements_file_path, \"rb+\") as file_obj:\n-        fix_requirements(file_obj)\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex e5b4d00c2c..3194e16bc9 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -28,7 +28,6 @@ dependencies = [\n     \"omegaconf>=2.1.1\",\n     \"parse>=1.19.0\",\n     \"pluggy>=1.0\",\n-    \"pre-commit-hooks\",\n     \"PyYAML>=4.2,<7.0\",\n     \"rich>=12.0,<15.0\",\n     \"toml>=0.10.0\",\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Drop unneeded dependencies\n- `importlib-metadata`: `importlib.metadata` was introduced in Python 3.8, we can probably use the stdlib now\n- `importlib-resources`: `importlib.resources.files` was introduced in Python 3.9\n- `rope`: unused after we dropped micropackaging in #4746\n\nExtras:\n\n- `pre-commit-hooks`: Added in #3436, it was pulled for just 1 function and is a blocker for Pyodide/PyScript support https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/discussions/4278 but it requires vendoring the logic\n", "hints_text": "- #4965 for `importlib_resources` & `rope`\n- `importlib-metadata` blocked by #4966 \n- `pre-commit-hooks` TODO\n\n", "all_hints_text": "- #4965 for `importlib_resources` & `rope`\n- `importlib-metadata` blocked by #4966 \n- `pre-commit-hooks` TODO\nI need opinions which way would be best to deal with removal of `pre-commit-hooks` from dependencies. For context, we use it for the one function `fix_requirements` which sorts the `requirements.txt` while preserving comments and was added in #3436 It is used while creation of a new project in `post_gen_hooks` in the starters & new blank project template.\n- One way is to copy over the `fix_requirements()` function or something similar into our code base and use it\n- The other is to get rid of this sorting. Remove `sort_requirements` first from `spaceflights-pandas` and `spaceflights-pyspark` (https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro-starters/pull/289) and then from Kedro code base. \nSorting the requirements files in alphabetic order is nice but doesn't merit adding another dependency I think, especially one that is used for development so often and might clash with user environments.\n\nThe full logic is 150 lines of code and it's MIT licensed https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks/blob/v5.0.0/pre_commit_hooks/requirements_txt_fixer.py either we vendor it ourselves, or we proceed with removing this functionality.\nI'm leaning towards removing the sorting of requirements, confirmed with @SajidAlamQB in https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro-starters/pull/289 that it's safe to do. @astrojuanlu \nI'd be in favor of removing the sorting of requirements as well. After we moved the main source of requirements to pyproject.toml that whole function became kind of a vestigial thing. If it's not gonna make any linter scream or anything of the sort, it's more advantageous to remove a dependency instead of adding something else that we'd have to maintain.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/3f1271724115c1f70866b62ff1c2fb4bc515f67e", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/467960fbbd570f03a995099ffb16d2355d23c64e", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/dcbff4f6c792475c376b5fd965303e89016c48ef", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/1a832594a68e8a0ec7b50b75a169303c2813a2e6", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/b021af54189262bb7c51283a8446e4691c1dbf25", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/d52536edb50fe7e4f5698f0f085fb414b1554105"], "created_at": "2025-07-14T14:53:54Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 5410, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-5410", "issue_numbers": [4980], "base_commit": "ee781f7c715b6832c018647a3cd41efa8afb4a58", "patch": "diff --git a/RELEASE.md b/RELEASE.md\nindex e262934b15..ca526bf5b2 100644\n--- a/RELEASE.md\n+++ b/RELEASE.md\n@@ -13,6 +13,7 @@\n ## Bug fixes and other changes\n * Removed the `cachetools` dependency and replaced it with a lightweight internal caching implementation.\n * Added a warning when a node returns a value but is defined with `outputs=None`, clarifying that the return value is ignored.\n+* Added util method `find_config_file()` to handle different config file extensions (.yml, .yaml)\n \n ## Documentation changes\n ## Community contributions\n@@ -65,6 +66,7 @@ Many thanks to the following Kedroids for contributing PRs to this release:\n * [Aseem Sangalay](https://github.com/aseemsangalay)\n * [Chris Schopp](https://github.com/chrisschopp)\n * [Yaroslav Halchenko](https://github.com/yarikoptic)\n+* [Camille Coeurjoly] (https://github.com/Camille1992)\n \n # Release 1.0.0\n ## Major features and improvements\ndiff --git a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\nindex 53b326c712..359c399d55 100644\n--- a/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n+++ b/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py\n@@ -21,6 +21,7 @@\n \n from kedro.io import CatalogProtocol\n from kedro.pipeline import Pipeline, pipeline\n+from kedro.utils import find_config_file\n \n if TYPE_CHECKING:\n     import types\n@@ -242,7 +243,7 @@ def __init__(self) -> None:\n         environment variable KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG (defaults to conf/logging.yml).\"\"\"\n         logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n         user_logging_path = os.environ.get(\"KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG\")\n-        project_logging_path = Path(\"conf/logging.yml\")\n+        project_logging_path = find_config_file(\"conf/logging\")\n         default_logging_path = Path(\n             Path(__file__).parent / \"rich_logging.yml\"\n             if importlib.util.find_spec(\"rich\")\n@@ -254,7 +255,7 @@ def __init__(self) -> None:\n         if user_logging_path:\n             path = user_logging_path\n \n-        elif project_logging_path.exists():\n+        elif project_logging_path is not None:\n             path = project_logging_path\n             msg = \"You can change this by setting the KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG environment variable accordingly.\"\n         else:\ndiff --git a/kedro/utils.py b/kedro/utils.py\nindex 10f1252485..5f4b8e5754 100644\n--- a/kedro/utils.py\n+++ b/kedro/utils.py\n@@ -32,6 +32,9 @@\n )\n PROTOCOL_DELIMITER = \"://\"\n \n+# Config extensions\n+_CONFIG_EXTENSIONS = (\".yml\", \".yaml\")\n+\n \n def _parse_filepath(filepath: str) -> dict[str, str]:\n     \"\"\"Split filepath on protocol and path. Based on `fsspec.utils.infer_storage_options`.\n@@ -257,3 +260,22 @@ def new_init(self, *args, **kwargs):  # type: ignore[no-untyped-def]\n         return obj\n \n     return obj\n+\n+\n+def find_config_file(\n+    filename: str, extensions: tuple[str, ...] = _CONFIG_EXTENSIONS\n+) -> Path | None:\n+    \"\"\"Find a config file in the current working directory.\n+\n+    Args:\n+        filename: The name of the config file to find.\n+        extensions: The extensions of the config file to find.\n+\n+    Returns:\n+        The path to the config file if found, otherwise None.\n+    \"\"\"\n+    path = Path(filename)\n+    return next(\n+        (path.with_suffix(ext) for ext in extensions if path.with_suffix(ext).exists()),\n+        None,\n+    )\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/framework/project/test_logging.py b/tests/framework/project/test_logging.py\nindex 68ec8adc96..e91fae9700 100644\n--- a/tests/framework/project/test_logging.py\n+++ b/tests/framework/project/test_logging.py\n@@ -40,8 +40,12 @@ def test_project_logging_in_default_logging_config(default_logging_config_with_p\n     assert logging.getLogger(\"test_project\").level == logging.INFO\n \n \n-def test_environment_variable_logging_config(monkeypatch, tmp_path):\n-    config_path = Path(tmp_path) / \"logging.yml\"\n+@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n+    \"logging_filename\",\n+    [\"logging.yml\", \"logging.yaml\"],\n+)\n+def test_environment_variable_logging_config(monkeypatch, tmp_path, logging_filename):\n+    config_path = Path(tmp_path) / logging_filename\n     monkeypatch.setenv(\"KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG\", config_path.absolute())\n     logging_config = {\"version\": 1, \"loggers\": {\"kedro\": {\"level\": \"WARNING\"}}}\n     with config_path.open(\"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n@@ -172,8 +176,12 @@ def test_has_rich_handler():\n         assert not _has_rich_handler(test_logger)\n \n \n-def test_default_logging_info_emission(monkeypatch, tmp_path, caplog):\n-    config_path = (Path(tmp_path) / \"conf\" / \"logging.yml\").absolute()\n+@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n+    \"logging_filename\",\n+    [\"logging.yml\", \"logging.yaml\"],\n+)\n+def test_default_logging_info_emission(monkeypatch, tmp_path, caplog, logging_filename):\n+    config_path = (Path(tmp_path) / \"conf\" / logging_filename).absolute()\n     config_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True)\n     logging_config = {\"version\": 1, \"loggers\": {\"kedro\": {\"level\": \"DEBUG\"}}}\n     with config_path.open(\"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\ndiff --git a/tests/test_utils.py b/tests/test_utils.py\nindex d047636508..54966de649 100644\n--- a/tests/test_utils.py\n+++ b/tests/test_utils.py\n@@ -5,7 +5,12 @@\n \n import pytest\n \n-from kedro.utils import KedroExperimentalWarning, experimental, load_obj\n+from kedro.utils import (\n+    KedroExperimentalWarning,\n+    experimental,\n+    find_config_file,\n+    load_obj,\n+)\n \n T = TypeVar(\"T\")\n \n@@ -233,3 +238,22 @@ def __init__(self, x):\n         A(3)  # no warning\n \n     assert len([x for x in w if issubclass(x.category, KedroExperimentalWarning)]) == 1\n+\n+\n+@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n+    \"filename, expected_suffix\",\n+    [\n+        (\"conf/logging\", \".yml\"),\n+        (\"conf/logging\", \".yaml\"),\n+    ],\n+)\n+def test_find_config_file(tmp_path, monkeypatch, filename, expected_suffix):\n+    monkeypatch.chdir(tmp_path)\n+    config_file = tmp_path / f\"{filename}{expected_suffix}\"\n+    config_file.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n+    config_file.touch()\n+\n+    result = find_config_file(filename)\n+\n+    assert result is not None\n+    assert result.suffix == expected_suffix\n", "problem_statement": "`logging.yaml` Is Not Automatically Detected With Alternative File Extension\n## Description\nThe logging behavior in Kedro can be stated by modifying the `logging.yml` in the `conf` folder. By default, Kedro searches for this file under `<PROJECT_ROOT>/conf` and sets it as default logging configuration. However, if the file features another file extension, e.g. `.yaml` instead of `.yml`, this mechanism no longer works. \n\n## Context\nThe [official YAML documentation](https://yaml.org/faq.html) recommends using the file extension `.yaml` if possible. When you following this guideline, Kedro will no longer be able to read the logging configuration file correctly.\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n1. Rename `conf/logging.yml` to `conf/logging.yaml`.\n2. Run Kedro. No specified logging behavior will be applied.\n\n## Expected Result\nKedro should accept `logging.yml` as well as `logging.yaml` as default. If this is not possible, `logging.yaml` has to be preferred according to the official recommendation.\n\n## Actual Result\nIf you name the file `logging.yaml`, it will be ignored.\n\n## Your Environment\n* Kedro version used (`pip show kedro` or `kedro -V`): 0.19.12\n* Python version used (`python -V`): 3.12\n* Operating system and version: Windows 10\n\n", "hints_text": "Thanks @mgreshake for opening this issue.\n\nIndeed, this logic is hardcoded here\n\nhttps://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/5416ff04f3d59154ebb99d9531dcb7992489e5c4/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py#L246-L263\n\nFor now, your workaround is to manually configure `KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG`.\n\n---\n\nAs for Kedro's general preference for `.yml` over the officially recommended `.yaml`... if we wanted to allow the latter more broadly, we would need to handle it with care. A quick search yielded hardcoded extensions in different parts of the codebase:\n\nhttps://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/5416ff04f3d59154ebb99d9531dcb7992489e5c4/kedro/framework/cli/pipeline.py#L173-L178\n\nNot saying it won't happen, but it's clearly a significant effort to do it right in exchange of little gain.\nFor most config (parameter, catalog etc) it should be possible to use both extensions. But like @astrojuanlu pointed out, it does look like we've hard coded the preference for `yml` in some places. \n\nI'll put this on the backlog, but it won't be a priority at the moment to fix this. We're happy to accept contributions!\nOops, I was just gonna move this from Wizard board to backlog. \nI would like to do this one with @Camille1992\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thanks @mgreshake for opening this issue.\n\nIndeed, this logic is hardcoded here\n\nhttps://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/5416ff04f3d59154ebb99d9531dcb7992489e5c4/kedro/framework/project/__init__.py#L246-L263\n\nFor now, your workaround is to manually configure `KEDRO_LOGGING_CONFIG`.\n\n---\n\nAs for Kedro's general preference for `.yml` over the officially recommended `.yaml`... if we wanted to allow the latter more broadly, we would need to handle it with care. A quick search yielded hardcoded extensions in different parts of the codebase:\n\nhttps://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/blob/5416ff04f3d59154ebb99d9531dcb7992489e5c4/kedro/framework/cli/pipeline.py#L173-L178\n\nNot saying it won't happen, but it's clearly a significant effort to do it right in exchange of little gain.\nFor most config (parameter, catalog etc) it should be possible to use both extensions. But like @astrojuanlu pointed out, it does look like we've hard coded the preference for `yml` in some places. \n\nI'll put this on the backlog, but it won't be a priority at the moment to fix this. We're happy to accept contributions!\nOops, I was just gonna move this from Wizard board to backlog. \nI would like to do this one with @Camille1992\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/4ce0d61cc0398a77cea4a19078baa3fd053f691b", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/a3493e9ecd2bcb11d6b8348a44a2d37471478cb2", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/00c8a9ca9be651e51e0eeb615cd6bc308e49b771"], "created_at": "2026-02-27T18:54:16Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 5469, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-5469", "issue_numbers": [5021], "base_commit": "d7c3fa8950649c8d4003b454104255df001a9523", "patch": "diff --git a/kedro/pipeline/node.py b/kedro/pipeline/node.py\nindex e5dd4ae88e..93d0cfb0b4 100644\n--- a/kedro/pipeline/node.py\n+++ b/kedro/pipeline/node.py\n@@ -744,6 +744,9 @@ def _node_error_message(msg: str) -> str:\n     )\n \n \n+_DOTTED_DATASET_NAME_WARNED = \"__dotted_dataset_name_warned__\"\n+\n+\n def _node_dataset_name_validation(name: str, namespace: str | None) -> None:\n     \"\"\"Validate the dataset name. The node inputs and outputs should not contain\n     '.' characters. This is to ensure that the dot notation is reserved for Kedro's\n@@ -763,12 +766,15 @@ def _node_dataset_name_validation(name: str, namespace: str | None) -> None:\n         if not namespace or not name_namespace.startswith(\n             namespace.split(\".\")[0]\n         ):  # match with top level namespace\n-            warnings.warn(\n-                f\"Dataset name '{name}' contains '.' characters, which is \"\n-                f\"not recommended as the dot notation is reserved for automatic \"\n-                f\"namespacing in Kedro. Consider using a different naming convention.\",\n-                UserWarning,\n-            )\n+            if not getattr(Node, _DOTTED_DATASET_NAME_WARNED, False):\n+                setattr(Node, _DOTTED_DATASET_NAME_WARNED, True)\n+                warnings.warn(\n+                    \"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters, which is \"\n+                    \"not recommended as the dot notation is reserved for automatic \"\n+                    \"namespacing in Kedro. Consider using a different naming convention.\",\n+                    UserWarning,\n+                    stacklevel=3,\n+                )\n \n \n def node(  # noqa: PLR0913\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/pipeline/conftest.py b/tests/pipeline/conftest.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..148c5182f8\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/tests/pipeline/conftest.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,13 @@\n+import pytest\n+\n+\n+@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n+def reset_dotted_dataset_name_warned():\n+    \"\"\"Reset the dotted dataset name warning flag before and after each test.\"\"\"\n+    from kedro.pipeline.node import Node\n+\n+    if hasattr(Node, \"__dotted_dataset_name_warned__\"):\n+        delattr(Node, \"__dotted_dataset_name_warned__\")\n+    yield\n+    if hasattr(Node, \"__dotted_dataset_name_warned__\"):\n+        delattr(Node, \"__dotted_dataset_name_warned__\")\ndiff --git a/tests/pipeline/test_node.py b/tests/pipeline/test_node.py\nindex 35a99b1d23..7a8ea51c53 100644\n--- a/tests/pipeline/test_node.py\n+++ b/tests/pipeline/test_node.py\n@@ -486,7 +486,7 @@ def test_invalid_namespaced_inputs(self):\n         \"\"\"Test that inputs with mismatched namespaces raise a ValueError.\"\"\"\n         with pytest.warns(\n             UserWarning,\n-            match=\"Dataset name 'wrong_namespace.input_dataset' contains '.' characters\",\n+            match=\"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters\",\n         ):\n             node(\n                 func=self.dummy_function,\n@@ -499,7 +499,7 @@ def test_invalid_namespaced_outputs(self):\n         \"\"\"Test that outputs with mismatched namespaces raise a ValueError.\"\"\"\n         with pytest.warns(\n             UserWarning,\n-            match=\"Dataset name 'wrong_namespace.output_dataset' contains '.' characters\",\n+            match=\"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters\",\n         ):\n             node(\n                 func=self.dummy_function,\n@@ -521,7 +521,7 @@ def test_valid_params_prefixed_inputs(self):\n     def test_invalid_inputs_with_dot_no_namespace(self):\n         \"\"\"Test that inputs with '.' but no namespace raise a ValueError.\"\"\"\n         with pytest.warns(\n-            UserWarning, match=\"Dataset name 'input.dataset' contains '.' characters\"\n+            UserWarning, match=\"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters\"\n         ):\n             node(\n                 func=self.dummy_function,\n@@ -532,7 +532,7 @@ def test_invalid_inputs_with_dot_no_namespace(self):\n     def test_invalid_outputs_with_dot_no_namespace(self):\n         \"\"\"Test that outputs with '.' but no namespace raise a ValueError.\"\"\"\n         with pytest.warns(\n-            UserWarning, match=\"Dataset name 'output.dataset' contains '.' characters\"\n+            UserWarning, match=\"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters\"\n         ):\n             node(\n                 func=self.dummy_function,\n@@ -566,7 +566,7 @@ def test_mismatched_namespace(self):\n         \"\"\"Test that mismatched namespaces in inputs and outputs raise a UserWarning.\"\"\"\n         with pytest.warns(\n             UserWarning,\n-            match=\"Dataset name 'other_namespace.output_dataset' contains '.' characters\",\n+            match=\"One or more dataset names contain '.' characters\",\n         ):\n             node(\n                 func=self.dummy_function,\n@@ -575,6 +575,37 @@ def test_mismatched_namespace(self):\n                 namespace=\"namespace\",\n             )\n \n+    def test_dotted_dataset_name_warns_only_once(self):\n+        \"\"\"Test that the dotted dataset name warning is only triggered once per run.\"\"\"\n+        import warnings\n+\n+        with warnings.catch_warnings(record=True) as warning_list:\n+            warnings.simplefilter(\"always\")\n+\n+            node(\n+                func=self.dummy_function,\n+                inputs=\"first.dataset\",\n+                outputs=\"output_dataset\",\n+            )\n+            node(\n+                func=self.dummy_function,\n+                inputs=\"second.dataset\",\n+                outputs=\"output_dataset2\",\n+            )\n+            node(\n+                func=self.dummy_function,\n+                inputs=\"third.dataset\",\n+                outputs=\"output_dataset3\",\n+            )\n+\n+        dot_warnings = [\n+            w\n+            for w in warning_list\n+            if issubclass(w.category, UserWarning)\n+            and \"contain '.' characters\" in str(w.message)\n+        ]\n+        assert len(dot_warnings) == 1\n+\n \n class TestNodePreviewPayload:\n     def test_text_preview(self):\n", "problem_statement": "Warnings for using '.' in dataset name.\n## Description\nSince I upgraded to kedro 1.0.0 from 0.19.12 I get a lot of warning messages for using '.' in my dataset names.\n\n## Context\nMy first pipeline only has a 2 level namespace so I can create a dataset for each of the coverage.model variants. The second pipeline uses a 3 level namespace so that I can apply separate coverage level filters as defined in my parameters and save each individual dataset accordingly. If i change the '.' to  '_' in the catalog (e.g. {product}.{sponsor}.{coverage}_{model}_policies_filtered), the second pipeline will not be able to find this dataset in the catalog. \n\nOriginally I had the dataset defined as \"{product}.{sponsor}.{coverage}.{model}.policies_filtered\" in kedro 0.19.12\n\nIs there a better way to implement this or will I have to disable the warning messages?\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\nPipeline 1:\n```      \nfor product, sponsors in settings.DYNAMIC_PIPELINE_MAPPING.items():\n        for sponsor, coverages in sponsors.items():\n            for coverage, models in coverages.items():\n                for model in models:\n                    _pipeline.append(\n                        pipeline(\n                            nodes=[\n                                Node(\n                                    func=rename_columns,\n                                    inputs=[\n                                        f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_dtype\",\n                                        \"params:policy_rename_cols\",\n                                    ],\n                                    outputs=f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_renamed\",\n                                ),\n                                Node(\n                                    func=process_policy_func,\n                                    inputs=[f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_renamed\"],\n                                    outputs=f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_cleaned\",\n                                ),\n                                Node(\n                                    func=filter_df,\n                                    inputs=[\n                                        f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_cleaned\",\n                                        f\"params:{coverage}.{model}.policy_filter\",\n                                    ],\n                                    outputs=f\"{coverage}.{model}_policies_filtered\",\n                                ),\n                            ],\n                            namespace=f\"{product}.{sponsor}\",\n                            tags=[coverage, model],\n                        )\n                    )\n\n    return sum(_pipeline)\n```     \n\n\nPipeline 2:\n```     \n  for product, sponsors in settings.DYNAMIC_PIPELINE_MAPPING.items():\n        for sponsor, coverages in sponsors.items():\n            for coverage, models in coverages.items():\n                for model in models:\n                    _pipeline.append(\n                        pipeline(\n                            nodes=[\n                                Node(\n                                    func=group_data,\n                                    inputs=[\n                                        f\"{model}_claims_cleaned\",\n                                        f\"params:claim_grouping\",\n                                        f\"params:claim_aggregates\",\n                                    ],\n                                    outputs=f\"{model}_claims_grouped\",\n                                ),\n                                Node(\n                                    func=merge_data,\n                                    inputs=[\n                                        f\"{model}_policies_earned_exposure\",\n                                        f\"{model}_claims_grouped\",\n                                        f\"params:left_key\",\n                                        f\"params:right_key\",\n                                        f\"params:merge_method\",\n                                    ],\n                                    outputs=f\"{model}_merged_policy_claim\",\n                                ),\n                            ],\n                            namespace=f\"{product}.{sponsor}.{coverage}\",\n                            tags=[sponsor, coverage, model],\n                        )\n                    )\n\n    return sum(_pipeline)\n```     \n\n## Your Environment\nKedro 1.0.0\n\n\n", "hints_text": "Hi @thomasdurkin, thanks for flagging this. The warning was a deliberate change to address https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/issues/3080. It's supposed to only warn for top-level namespaces (https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/pull/4797), but with a nested setup like yours it might indeed warn more than expected. @DimedS @ankatiyar any thoughts on this?\n> [@DimedS](https://github.com/DimedS) [@ankatiyar](https://github.com/ankatiyar) any thoughts on this?\n\nIt's great that we changed this from an error to a warning. To avoid overwhelming users with advanced cases, we could consider limiting the warning to once per run.\n@DimedS A single warning would be great for advanced cases. Unless there is a better way for me to setup my dynamic pipelines.\n\nAny update on this? Thank you!\nHi @thomasdurkin  we\u2019ve added this as a Hacktoberfest ticket so the community can help out.\nIf no one picks it up during the event, we\u2019ll handle it after. \nIf you\u2019d like to contribute as part of Hacktoberfest, we\u2019d really appreciate it!\nI'm also being spammed by these warnings, as I am using the following convention for my catalog entries:\n\n```\n{pipeline_name}.{layer}.{dataset_name}\n```\n\nWould be good to have a solution!\n\n*edit*\n\nCurrent workaround:\n\n```python\nimport warnings\n\n\n# Ignore dataset dot notations due to namespae changes\n# https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/issues/5021\nwarnings.filterwarnings(\n    \"ignore\",\n    message=(\n        r\".*contains '\\.' characters, which is not recommended as the dot notation \"\n        r\"is reserved for automatic namespacing in Kedro.*\"\n    ),\n    category=UserWarning,\n)\n```\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Hi @thomasdurkin, thanks for flagging this. The warning was a deliberate change to address https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/issues/3080. It's supposed to only warn for top-level namespaces (https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/pull/4797), but with a nested setup like yours it might indeed warn more than expected. @DimedS @ankatiyar any thoughts on this?\n> [@DimedS](https://github.com/DimedS) [@ankatiyar](https://github.com/ankatiyar) any thoughts on this?\n\nIt's great that we changed this from an error to a warning. To avoid overwhelming users with advanced cases, we could consider limiting the warning to once per run.\n@DimedS A single warning would be great for advanced cases. Unless there is a better way for me to setup my dynamic pipelines.\n\nAny update on this? Thank you!\nHi @thomasdurkin  we\u2019ve added this as a Hacktoberfest ticket so the community can help out.\nIf no one picks it up during the event, we\u2019ll handle it after. \nIf you\u2019d like to contribute as part of Hacktoberfest, we\u2019d really appreciate it!\nI'm also being spammed by these warnings, as I am using the following convention for my catalog entries:\n\n```\n{pipeline_name}.{layer}.{dataset_name}\n```\n\nWould be good to have a solution!\n\n*edit*\n\nCurrent workaround:\n\n```python\nimport warnings\n\n\n# Ignore dataset dot notations due to namespae changes\n# https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/issues/5021\nwarnings.filterwarnings(\n    \"ignore\",\n    message=(\n        r\".*contains '\\.' characters, which is not recommended as the dot notation \"\n        r\"is reserved for automatic namespacing in Kedro.*\"\n    ),\n    category=UserWarning,\n)\n```\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/f545fba3d7e85aa78e69f6736bb53a7fc1be591f", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/0e96f90eaaaef31d1b069bbabce198debae21d7b", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/61fa6e6b127f30f598be5dc218d1de1f06bcbef8", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/9d6e04a3f6d8098eef8578bf40cd73e124250327", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/0ef535025ad3cd72fdd014444c4b91a42c87eb60", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/78d154bd96de38190de4f2f20a9929f0b2a614a0", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/473e9f2abd3cabd1c7963069563d24daccfa1c93"], "created_at": "2026-03-26T23:31:31Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 1, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-1", "issue_numbers": [5069], "base_commit": "f2164cb8107cf265f80c8b0a13f68b718d1e44f3", "patch": "diff --git a/README.md b/README.md\nindex 4b0d3ad796..d1dff1b3c4 100644\n--- a/README.md\n+++ b/README.md\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-# kedro\n\\ No newline at end of file\n+# kedro\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Create a Kedro MCP Server\n## Description\n- Create basic MCP server (FastMCP).\n- Provide a way for users to run the MCP server locally on thier machine. E.g. Vizro did it via Docker. \n- Expose tools written for conversion + best practices in #5068, and #5067  .\n- Make the server available via a `kedro-mcp` repo.\n\n## Context\n<!-- Why is this change important to you? How would you use it? How can it benefit other users? -->\n\n## Possible Implementation\n<!-- (Optional) Suggest an idea for implementing the addition or change. -->\n\n## Possible Alternatives\n<!-- (Optional) Describe any alternative solutions or features you've considered. -->\n\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/ecacce8c7f1c061e4e3f07cfb27d1e4252603d89"], "created_at": "2019-04-25T14:12:24Z"}
{"repo": "kedro-org/kedro", "pull_number": 5460, "instance_id": "kedro-org__kedro-5460", "issue_numbers": [5105], "base_commit": "d1af1822687a438a0f3fba8913a919d06e02c298", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/stylesheets/mermaid.css b/docs/stylesheets/mermaid.css\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..ee97a27deb\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/docs/stylesheets/mermaid.css\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+/* Mermaid light mode - Kedro branding */\n+[data-md-color-scheme=\"default\"] {\n+  --md-mermaid-node-bg-color: #FFF7E2;\n+  --md-mermaid-node-fg-color: #FFC900;\n+  --md-mermaid-label-bg-color: #FFF7E2;\n+  --md-mermaid-label-fg-color: #000000;\n+  --md-mermaid-edge-color: #000000;\n+}\n+\n+/* Mermaid dark mode - Kedro branding */\n+[data-md-color-scheme=\"slate\"] {\n+  --md-mermaid-node-bg-color: #636363;\n+  --md-mermaid-node-fg-color: #FFC900;\n+  --md-mermaid-label-bg-color: #636363;\n+  --md-mermaid-label-fg-color: #FFFFFF;\n+  --md-mermaid-edge-color: #FFFFFF;\n+}\ndiff --git a/mkdocs.yml b/mkdocs.yml\nindex eddaaaf04a..f74f013ee0 100755\n--- a/mkdocs.yml\n+++ b/mkdocs.yml\n@@ -8,13 +8,13 @@ theme:\n   custom_dir: docs/overrides/\n   palette:\n     # Palette toggle for light mode\n-    - scheme: light\n+    - scheme: default\n       toggle:\n         icon: material/white-balance-sunny\n         name: Switch to dark mode\n \n     # Palette toggle for dark mode\n-    - scheme: dark\n+    - scheme: slate\n       toggle:\n         icon: material/white-balance-sunny\n         name: Switch to light mode\n@@ -51,7 +51,7 @@ theme:\n plugins:\n   - search\n   - autorefs\n-  - mermaid2\n+  - mermaid2:\n   - redirects:\n       redirect_maps:\n         'configuration/telemetry.md': 'about/telemetry.md'\n@@ -287,12 +287,14 @@ extra_css:\n   - stylesheets/themes.css\n   - stylesheets/footer.css\n   - stylesheets/welcome.css\n+   - stylesheets/mermaid.css\n \n extra_javascript:\n   - javascript/readthedocs.js\n   - javascript/deindex-old-docs.js\n \n \n+\n nav:\n   - Welcome: index.md\n   - Kedro:\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "docs: investigate on how to change the theme for mermaid diagram\n## Description\nWe currently use mkdocs mermaid to render most of our technical diagrams. However, it applies its own default theme, which makes the diagrams difficult to read in dark mode. We need to adjust the diagram colours to improve visibility.\n\nFor example, the diagram on this page is not very clear in dark theme:\nhttps://docs.kedro.org/en/1.0.0/deploy/#overview\n\n<img width=\"1458\" height=\"884\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b3f51c8a-d88e-4068-bfe2-f9ca0501dcfb\" />\n\nIt looks like others have encountered the same issue as well:\nhttps://github.com/squidfunk/mkdocs-material/discussions/4582\n\n## Task\nInvestigate how the theme of mermaid diagrams in `mkdocs` can be changed. Propose a solution in this issue.\n", "hints_text": "I will take this one! feel free to join me!\n@merelcht \nI try to change the mermaid theme based on: https://mkdocs-mermaid2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#other-themes, but it doesn't work.\nHere is my branch with small modification: https://github.com/chuxiaoyu/kedro/tree/mermaid-theme\n\n<img width=\"1714\" height=\"965\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/39461369-0b10-4d57-9cc5-a34e594703a2\" />\n\nHi, I'm a first time contributor and would love to work on this issue. I'll investigate the Mermaid theme configuration in mkdocs material and propose a solution. I ll be Happy to receive any guidance from the team.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I will take this one! feel free to join me!\n@merelcht \nI try to change the mermaid theme based on: https://mkdocs-mermaid2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#other-themes, but it doesn't work.\nHere is my branch with small modification: https://github.com/chuxiaoyu/kedro/tree/mermaid-theme\n\n<img width=\"1714\" height=\"965\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/39461369-0b10-4d57-9cc5-a34e594703a2\" />\n\nHi, I'm a first time contributor and would love to work on this issue. I'll investigate the Mermaid theme configuration in mkdocs material and propose a solution. I ll be Happy to receive any guidance from the team.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/00a349871a22eb4563ea7629a3f5f8128dfe44c2", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/7b54190f27bd0acd9744279244e814403d834a3c", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/75045c4e1c9032d5e5063109e5a6780b7f0a4b77", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/fd261466b041cafd842e049ce42412a9f5b53be5", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/e4a9e44c960a74031284e0c99c317186d839a98a", "https://github.com/kedro-org/kedro/commit/82dcf11650eac0fc5791b1382b3d7f04b39e8b8f"], "created_at": "2026-03-21T13:57:20Z"}
